Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code contains **two** patterns from the migration guide:

| API | Pattern | Line |
|-----|---------|------|
| `thread.Abort()` | **Timeout enforcement** — aborting a thread exceeding a time limit | called after `Join` fails |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` | **ThreadAbortException as control flow** — swallowing the abort inside the worker | inner try/catch |

In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone entirely.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Blocks until the task completes or the timeout fires.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout.
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => work(), token)` | Task-based model; the token prevents scheduling if already cancelled |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult()` | `WaitAsync` (.NET 6+) makes the wait itself cancellable |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation replaces forced abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException) { ResetAbort(); }` | Removed entirely | No abort exception exists; `OperationCanceledException` is caught at the caller |

## ⚠️ Critical Pitfall: Uncooperative Work

The **fundamental behavior change** is that `work()` is **no longer forcibly terminated**. If `work()` is a long-running CPU-bound operation that never checks for cancellation, the task keeps running in the background after the timeout fires — you just stop *waiting* for it.

To make `work` actually stop, pass the token through:

```csharp
// Change the signature to accept a token:
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;
    Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
    // ... same as above
}

// Caller cooperates by checking the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **Forgetting `using` on `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` doesn't cancel the task itself** | It only stops waiting. The underlying task runs until `work()` hits a checkpoint or finishes. Design checkpoints based on acceptable cancellation latency. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from unrelated cancellations. |
| **Blocking calls inside `work()` (e.g., `Thread.Sleep`)** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O that accepts a `CancellationToken`, otherwise the work won't respond to cancellation while blocked. |
